# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: frank-kendon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] Campbell was born at Blantyre, near Hamilton, Lanarkshire, Scotland in 1885, and received his education at Hamilton Academy and Fettes College, in Edinburgh.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] In 1904 he went up to St John's College, Cambridge, receiving a Bachelor of Arts degree in 1907.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] After graduation Campbell worked as a lecturer in Classics at the University of Liverpool and the University of Reading before returning to St.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] In 1922 he was appointed as Gladstone Professor of Greek at the University of Liverpool, a position he held until his retirement 1950.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] Campbell lived in Cambridge until his death, but taught at the University of Bristol during the year of 1954.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] Campbell married, and had two daughters and one son.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] Campbell worked on the emendation of *Horace* (1924) and published this as *Horace Odes and Epodes* (University of Liverpool Press, 1953).
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] In addition to publishing different editions of Horace, Campbell also worked on emending classical texts, such as Euripides and Aeschylus.
[src:frank-kendon/a-y-campbell] *The Agamemnon of Aeschylus* (1936) is his emendation of the texts of Aeschylus.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:frank-kendon/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] The school was founded by a Baptist minister, The Reverend Joseph James Kendon, in 1866 and still places great emphasis on its Christian character.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Headmaster Francie Healy has been in post since September 2010.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Bethany School has a campus location set in 60 acres (24 ha) of countryside.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Bethany School has a wide variety of sports.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Rugby, football and cricket are among the most popular sports for boys, with netball, hockey and rounders for girls.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] The school also has other sports facilities, including fitness premises, and a 25-metre (82 ft), six-lane indoor swimming pool.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] A variety of clubs and activities, including beekeeping, archery, table tennis, and others are available to pupils and these are incorporated into the school day.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Bethany School takes part in the Duke of Edinburgh's Award scheme and each year 15-20 pupils achieve the Gold Award.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Business Studies pupils have the option in the Sixth Form of participating in Young Enterprise, a charity scheme, where pupils form a business and attempt to generate profits for shareholders.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] Bethany School has historically put a strong emphasis on community, and continues to do so.
[src:frank-kendon/bethany-school-goudhurst] The Bethanians' Society was founded in 1887 for the former pupils of the School.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] With a global sales presence, publishing hubs, and offices in more than 40 countries, it has published over 50,000 titles by authors from over 100 countries.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Its publications include more than 420 academic journals, monographs, reference works, school and university textbooks, and English language teaching and learning publications.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It also publishes Bibles, runs a bookshop in Cambridge, sells through Amazon, and has a conference venues business in Cambridge at the Pitt Building and the Sir Geoffrey Cass Sports and Social Centre.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press, as part of the University of Cambridge, is a non-profit organization.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press joined The Association of American Publishers trade organization in the *Hachette v.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Internet Archive* lawsuit which resulted in the removal of access to over 500,000 books from global readers.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press is the oldest university press in the world.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It originated from letters patent granted to the University of Cambridge by Henry VIII in 1534.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge was one of the two privileged presses (the other being Oxford University Press).
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Authors published by Cambridge have included John Milton, William Harvey, Isaac Newton, Bertrand Russell, and Stephen Hawking.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] University printing began in Cambridge when the first practising University Printer, Thomas Thomas, set up a printing house in 1584.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The first publication was a book, *Two Treatises of the Lord His Holie Supper*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1591, the first Cambridge Bible was printed by John Legate and in 1629, Cambridge folio edition of the King James Bible was printed by Thomas and John Buck.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In July 1697, the Duke of Somerset made a loan of £200 to the university "towards the printing house and press" and James Halman, Registrary of the university, lent £100 for the same purpose.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] A new home for the press, The Pitt Building, on Trumpington Street in the centre of Cambridge, was completed in 1833, and was designed by Edward Blore.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In the early 1800s, the press pioneers the development of stereotype printing, allowing successive printings from one setting.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press began using steam-powered machine presses by the 1850s.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It was in this period that the press turned down what later became the Oxford English Dictionary – a proposal for which was brought to Cambridge by James Murray before he turned to Oxford.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press journals publishing programme began in 1893 with the *Journal of Physiology* and then the *Journal of Hygiene and Biometrika*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] By 1910 the press had become a well-established journal publisher with a successful list which includes its first humanities title, *Modern Language Review*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] 1956 saw the first issue of the *Journal of Fluid Mechanics*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press has published >170 Nobel Prize winners, the first in 1895.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1913, the Monotype system of hot-metal mechanised typesetting was introduced at the press.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1949, the press opened its first international branch in New York.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press moved to its current site in Cambridge in 1963.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The mid-century modern building, University Printing House, was constructed in 1961–1963.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The building was designed by Beard, Bennett, Wilkins and Partners.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1975, the press launched its English language teaching publishing business.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1981, the press moved to a new site on Shaftsbury Road.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Edinburgh Building was purpose-built with an adjoining warehouse to accommodate the press's expansion.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It was built in 1979–80 by International Design and Construction.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The site was demolished in 2017 to make way for the construction of Cambridge Assessment's Triangle Building.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1989, the press acquired the long-established Bible and prayer-book publisher Eyre & Spottiswoode, which gave the press the ancient and unique title of The Queen's Printer.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1992, the press opened a bookshop at 1 Trinity Street, Cambridge, which was the oldest-known bookshop site in Britain, as books have been sold there since 1581.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2008 the shop expanded into 27 Market Hill where its specialist Education and English Language Teaching shop opened the following year.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press bookshop sells Press books as well as Cambridge souvenirs such as mugs, diaries, bags, postcards, maps.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1993, the Cass Centre was opened to provide sports and social facilities for employees and their families.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 1999, Cambridge Dictionaries Online was launched.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2012, the press sold its printing operation to MPG Books Group and now uses third parties around the world to provide its print publications.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the press released a new concept in scholarly publishing through Cambridge Elements where authors whose works are either too short to be printed as a book or too long to qualify as a journal article could have these published within 12 weeks.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, Cambridge University Press merged with Cambridge Assessment.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The new organisation was called Cambridge University Press & Assessment.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2022, Amira Bennison was elected chair of the Cambridge University Press academic committee, replacing Kenneth Armstrong.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press has stated its support for a sustainable transition to open access.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It offers a range of open access publishing options under the heading of Cambridge Open, allowing authors to comply with the Gold Open Access and Green Open Access requirements of major research funders.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It published Gold Open Access journals and books and works with publishing partners such as learned societies to develop Open Access for different communities.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It supports Green Open Access (also called Green archiving) across its journals and monographs, allowing authors to deposit content in institutional and subject-specific repositories.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It also supports sharing on commercial sharing sites through its Cambridge Core Share service.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In recent years it has entered into several Read & Publish Open Access agreements with university libraries and consortia in several countries, including a landmark agreement with the University of California.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In its 2019 Annual Report, Cambridge University Press stated that it saw such agreements "as an important stepping stone in the transition to Open Access".
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the press joined with the University of Cambridge's research and teaching departments to give a unified response to Plan S, which calls for all publications resulting from publicly funded research to be published in compliant open access journals or platforms from 2020.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The response emphasized Cambridge's commitment to an open access goal which works effectively for all academic disciplines, was financially sustainable for institutions and high-quality peer review, and which leads to an orderly transition.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Press is a member of the Open Access Scholarly Publishing Association and the International Association of STM Publishers.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2023, more than 50 per cent of Cambridge University Press research articles were in open access mode.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press was a non-teaching department of the University of Cambridge.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press has, since 1698, been governed by the press 'Syndics' (originally known as the 'Curators'), 18 senior members of the University of Cambridge who, along with other non-executive directors, bring a range of subject and business expertise.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Chair of the syndicate in 2021 was Professor Stephen Toope (Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge).
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The syndicate has delegated its powers to a Press & Assessment Board; and to an Academic Publishing Committee and an English Language Teaching & Education Publishing Committee.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Press & Assessment Board is responsible for setting overarching strategic direction.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Publishing Committees provide quality assurance and formal approval of the publishing strategy.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The operational responsibility of the press was delegated by the Syndics to the Secretary of the Syndicate and the Chief Executive.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] From 1 August 2021 onwards, Cambridge University Press became solely the academic and bible publishing division of Cambridge University Press & Assessment.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The English and education arms of the organisation merged with the equivalent departments of Cambridge Assessment to form new, merged divisions.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2011, Cambridge University Press adopted SAP software.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press works closely with IT services firm Tech Mahindra on SAP, and with Cognizant and Wipro on other systems.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2016, Cambridge Books Online and Cambridge Journals Online were replaced by Cambridge Core – a single platform to access its publishing ("the home of academic content from Cambridge University Press").
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] It provided significantly enhanced interfaces and upgraded navigation capabilities, as well as article-level and chapter-level content selection.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] A year after Cambridge Core went live, the press launched Cambridge Core Share, functionality to allow users to generate and share links with free access to selected journal articles, an early sign of the press's commitment to open research.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2020, Cambridge University Press partnered with online library Perlego to offer students access to digital textbooks.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The technology adapts and responds to users, "recommending course material needed to optimise learning".
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, the press began migrating its website onto Drupal.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In May 1940, CUP applied to the Inland Revenue for the exemption of its printing and publishing profits from taxation, equivalent to charitable status.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In November 1975, with CUP facing financial collapse, CUP's chief executive Geoffrey Cass wrote a 60-page "preliminary letter" to the Inland Revenue again seeking tax-exemption.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] A year later Cass's application was granted in a letter from the Inland Revenue, though the decision was not made public.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] After consulting CUP, Cambridge's 'sister' press, the giant Oxford University Press presented their own submission and received similar exemption.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2003 OUP's tax exemption was publicly attacked by Joel Rickett of The Bookseller in *The Guardian*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, with the new 'public benefit' requirement of the revised Charities Act, the issue was re-examined with particular reference to the OUP.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2008 CUP's and OUP's privilege was attacked by rival publishers.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2009 *The Guardian* invited author Andrew Malcolm to write an article on the subject.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, from the National Archives at Kew, Malcolm obtained scans of CUP's unsuccessful applications for tax-exemption made in the 1940s and 1950s and their later successful applications in the 1970s.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] He then indexed and posted these on the Akmedea website.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Late in 2020, the papers held at Kew were withdrawn from public access and ruled closed for 50 years until 1 January 2029.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] This rendered the scans on the website their only public source.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2021, the documents were cited in a discussion on the formation of Cambridge University Press & Assessment reported in the Cambridge University Reporter.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2007, controversy arose over the press's decision to destroy all remaining copies of its 2006 book *Alms for Jihad: Charity and Terrorism in the Islamic World*, by Burr and Collins, as part of the settlement of a lawsuit brought by Saudi billionaire Khalid bin Mahfouz.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Within hours, *Alms for Jihad* became one of the 100 most sought after titles on Amazon.com and eBay in the United States.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press sent a letter to libraries asking them to remove copies from circulation.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press subsequently sent out copies of an "errata" sheet for the book.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In the *New York Times Book Review* (7 October 2007), United States Congressman Frank R.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Wolf described Cambridge's settlement as "basically a book burning".
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press pointed out that, at that time, it had already sold most of its copies of the book.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press defended its actions, saying it had acted responsibly and that it was a global publisher with a duty to observe the laws of many different countries.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In this case, originally filed in 2008, CUP et al. accused Georgia State University of infringement of copyright.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The case closed on 29 September 2020, with GSU as the prevailing party.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] On 18 August 2017, following an "instruction" from a Chinese import agency, Cambridge University Press used the functionality that had been built into Cambridge Core to temporarily delete politically sensitive articles from *The China Quarterly* on its Chinese website.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The articles focused on topics China regards as taboo, including the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre, Mao Zedong's Cultural Revolution, the 2014 Hong Kong protests, and ethnic tensions in Xinjiang and Tibet.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] On 21 August 2017, in the face of growing international protests, Cambridge University Press announced it would immediately repost the articles to uphold the principle of academic freedom on which the university's work was founded.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In a discussion reported in the Cambridge University Reporter, D.K.K.Chow declared, "Without academic leadership on the matter, the University's basic ethical values were cast aside by commercial considerations.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] This instigated public debate, which would have been avoided had academic leadership been more vigilant, causing unnecessary damage to the University's reputation.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In February 2021, the forthcoming *Cambridge Handbook of Privatization* was found to have included a chapter by J.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Mark Ramseyer in which he described Koreans murdered in the Kantō Massacre of 1923 as "gangs" that "torched buildings, planted bombs, [and] poisoned water supplies".
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Editors Avihay Dorfman and Alon Harel acknowledged the historical distortions of the chapter, but gave Ramseyer a chance to revise.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Harel described the inclusion of the original chapter as an "innocent and very regrettable" mistake on the part of the editors.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Press undertakes community engagement in Cambridge and around the world where there are Press employees.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Annually, the press selects a UK Charity of the Year, which has included local charities Centre 33 (2016 and 2017), Rowan Humberstone (2018), and Castle School (2019).
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] On World Book Day 2016, the press held a digital Shakespeare publishing workshop for students and their teachers.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Similarly, their Indian office conducted a workshop for teachers and students in 17 schools in Delhi to learn the whole process of book publishing.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press donated more than 75,000 books in 2016.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] An apprenticeship programme for people interested in careers in publishing was established in 2016; by 2022 it had 200 active apprentices in the UK in a wide range of roles.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The Press monitors its emissions annually, has converted to energy-saving equipment, minimizes plastic use and ensures that their paper was sourced ethically.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] In 2019, the World Wildlife Fund awarded its highest score to the press of Three Trees, based on the press's timber purchasing policy, performance statement and its responsible sourcing of timber.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The press won the Independent Publishers Guild Independent Publishing Awards for sustainability in 2020 and in 2021.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Its public commitments to sustainability include being a signatory of the UN Global Compact and to the goals of the Cambridge Zero initiative run by the University of Cambridge – to being carbon zero on all energy-related emissions by 2048.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge University Press was a signatory of the SDG Publishers Compact, and has taken steps to support the achievement of the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) in the publishing industry.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] These include publishing a new set of open access journals known as Cambridge Prisms, relevant to the SDGs, that includes *Coastal Futures*, *Precision Medicine*, *Global Mental Health*, *Extinction*, *Plastics*, *Water* and *Drylands*.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] Cambridge also worked with the Association of Learned and Professional Society Publishers (ALPSP) to create the University Press Redux Sustainability Award in 2020.
[src:frank-kendon/cambridge-university-press] The inaugural award was given to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) for its SDG Pathfinder, an open-access digital discovery tool for finding content and data relating to the SDGs.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] In 1914 he joined the navy, where he rose to lieutenant.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] After the end of World War I he matriculated at St John's College, Cambridge on a scholarship; it was while at Cambridge that he edited an anthology of student poetry and met the writer J.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Priestley, who would remain a lifelong friend.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Davison emigrated to the United States in 1925, and became an academic, teaching at Vassar College, the University of Miami, and the University of Colorado at Boulder, where he was involved in the Colorado Writers 1937 conference.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] He was widely published as a poet in the 1920s, featured in the J.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Squire anthologies, and became known as a writer of sonnets.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] His *Be Thou At Peace* has been set to music by John Raynor.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Davison joined the United States Army in 1943, shortly after becoming a Naturalized citizen of the United States.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] He had previously served as a paymaster in the Royal Navy.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] During World War II, Davison attained the rank of Lieutenant colonel in the United States Army.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] He was named director of the Special Projects Division, which was responsible for overseeing the re-education of German prisoners of war.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Many of Davidson's poems from this time-frame appear to express doubts about the mission he had been assigned.
[src:frank-kendon/edward-davison-poet] Davidson had no knowledge of German language, culture, or politics, and so struggled to craft a suitable program.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] He was the son of Samuel Kendon, a schoolmaster at Bethany School, Goudhurst; the educator Olive Kendon was his sister.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] He matriculated in 1921 at St John's College, Cambridge, where he became a Fellow in 1948.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] Kendon was a published poet in the 1920s and later a writer of stories and a novel.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] From 1935 to 1954 he worked for Cambridge University Press.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] At the beginning of World War II he was a campaigning pacifist.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] After the war, he undertook the translations of the Psalms in the New English Bible, but died before he could complete the work.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] Timothy d'Arch Smith argued tentatively for Kendon's inclusion in the canon of Uranian poets in view of a poem, in *Poems and Sonnets*, singing the praises of naked bathing boys – a Uranian staple.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] Kendon had four children with his wife, Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:frank-kendon/frank-kendon] The children were in order of birth; Alice (nee Kendon, then Stephens then Thomas) a prolific linguist, Adam Kendon, Andrew a talented musician and artist, and Thomas (known as Adrian) who is the last surviving of the Kendon siblings, also a talented musician.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley's extramarital half-sister was Sally Grosvenor, Duchess of Westminster.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley's memoir *My Father and Myself* begins: "I was born in 1896 and my parents were married in 1919." Registered at birth as Joe Ackerley, he later took the middle name Randolph after his uncle, Randolph Payne, first husband of his mother's sister Bunny.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] As an adult, he published under his first two initials and surname.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His father, (Alfred) Roger Ackerley, was a successful fruit merchant known as the "Banana King" of London.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Roger Ackerley was first married to a young Swiss woman of wealthy parentage named (Charlotte) Louise Burckhardt (1862–1892) who died probably of tuberculosis, before they had children.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Louise was the subject of John Singer Sargent's painting, *Lady with the Rose*.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His mother was Janetta Aylward (known as Netta), an actress whom Roger met in Paris; the two returned to London together.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] They had an intermittent relationship, and three years later, in 1895, she gave birth to a son, Peter, then Joe a year later, and Nancy in 1899.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] According to Joe's maternal Aunt Bunny, Peter's birth, and likely all of them, were "accidents." She told him, "Your father happened to have run out of French letters that day," (when Peter was conceived).
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His father set up a household with his mother starting in 1903, after which the children saw him more regularly.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley was educated at Rossall School, a public and preparatory school in Fleetwood, Lancashire.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] During this time, he discovered he was attracted to other boys.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His striking good looks earned him the nickname "Girlie," but he was not very sexually active as a schoolboy.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His father gave him a generous allowance and never insisted that he follow him into the business.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] After the First World War broke out in August 1914, Ackerley was commissioned as a second lieutenant in September 1914.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He was assigned to the 8th Battalion of the East Surrey Regiment, part of the 18th Division, then stationed in East Anglia.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] On 1 July 1916, he was wounded at the Battle of the Somme.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He was shot in the arm and suffered shards of a whisky bottle becoming imbedded in his side from an explosion.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] After lying wounded in a shell-hole for six hours, he was rescued and sent home for sick-leave.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He soon volunteered to go back to the front.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He was promoted to captain, when his elder brother Peter, also an officer in the East Surrey Regiment, arrived in France in December 1916.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] At the time, Ackerley was his superior officer.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He later wrote that the cheerful Peter saluted his brother "gladly and conscientiously." In February 1917, Peter was wounded in action on a dangerous assignment.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Though Peter got back to the British lines, Ackerley never saw him again, as he was killed on 7 August 1918, two months before the end of the war.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Peter's death haunted Ackerley all his life; he suffered from survivor's guilt.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In May 1917, Ackerley led an attack in the Arras region where he was wounded, this time in the buttock and thigh.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] While he was waiting for help, the Germans arrived and took him prisoner.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] As an officer, he was assigned to an internment camp in neutral Switzerland, which was relatively comfortable.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Here he began his play, *The Prisoners of War,* which expresses the cabin fever of captivity and his frustrated longings for another English prisoner.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley was not repatriated to England until after the war ended.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Temporary Captain Ackerley relinquished his commission on completion of service, 24 April 1919.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] From the autumn of 1919, Ackerley attended Magdalene College, Cambridge, where he was in the same year as Patrick Blackett, Geoffrey Webb and Kingsley Martin.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] After graduating with a third-class degree in English in 1921, he moved to London, where he enjoyed the cosmopolitan capital and continued to write.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1923 his play *The Prisoners of War* was included in a collection of young British writers, so he began to receive some recognition.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Forster and other literary bright lights, but was lonely, despite numerous sexual partners.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] With his play having trouble finding a producer and feeling generally adrift and distant from his family, Ackerley turned to Forster for guidance.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Forster, whom he knew from *A Passage to India*, arranged a position as secretary to the Maharaja of Chhatarpur, Vishwanath Singh.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley spent about five months in India, which was still under British rule.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He developed a strong distaste for the several Anglo-Indians (British people living in India) he met.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley's comic memoir *Hindoo Holiday* explores some of his experiences.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] The Maharaja was homosexual, and His Majesty's obsessions and dalliances, along with Ackerley's observations about Anglo-Indians, account for much of the humour of the work.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In England, *The Prisoners of War* was finally produced in 1925, to some acclaim.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Its run began at The Three Hundred Club on 5 July 1925, then transferred to the Playhouse Theatre on 31 August.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley enjoyed his success, returning to London to carouse with its theatrical crowd.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Through Cambridge friends, he met John Gielgud and other rising stars of the stage.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1928 Ackerley joined the staff of the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He worked in the Talks Department, which arranged radio lectures by prominent scholars and public figures.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He helped to create the new department, which had an extensive influence on British literary and cultural life.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1935 Ackerley was appointed Literary Editor of the BBC's magazine *The Listener*.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He served in this position until 1959, discovering and promoting many younger writers, including W.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Auden, Christopher Isherwood, Philip Larkin, and Stephen Spender.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley was one of Francis King's two mentors (the other being C.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] From 1943, Ackerley lived in a small flat at Putney overlooking the Thames.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] It was in Star and Garter Mansions, which were situated above the large riverside pub of the same name.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Almost all his significant work was produced during this period.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He had a stable job at the BBC and ended the unsatisfying promiscuity of his younger years.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] What remained was his search for what he called an "Ideal Friend".
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley took financial responsibility for his sister Nancy, who was unstable, and his aging Aunt Bunny.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1946 (the year his mother died), he acquired an Alsatian dog named Queenie.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] The dog became his primary companion for the next 15 years.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] During this time, he was most productive.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He revised *Hindoo Holiday* (1952), completed *My Dog Tulip* (1956) and *We Think the World of You* (1960), and worked on drafts of *My Father and Myself*.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He visited Japan in 1960 to see his friend Francis King; he was very taken with the beauty of the scenery and even more with Japanese men.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley, who had lost a brother and both parents, described it as "the saddest day of my life." He said: "I would have immolated myself as a *suttee* when Queenie died.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] For no human would I ever have done such a thing, but by my love for Queenie I would have been irresistibly compelled." In 1962, *We Think the World of You* won the W.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Smith Literary Award, which came with a substantial cash prize, but this did little to stir him from his grief.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In the years after Queenie's death Ackerley worked on his memoir about his father and drank too much.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His sister Nancy found him dead in his bed on the morning of 4 June 1967.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley's biographer Peter Parker gives the cause of death as coronary thrombosis.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Toward the end of his life Ackerley sold 1,075 letters from Forster, dating from 1922 onwards, for which he received £6,000.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He said that it was "a sum of money which will enable Nancy and me to drink ourselves carelessly into our graves".
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley did not live long enough to enjoy the money, but, together with the royalties from his existing works and posthumous works, it allowed Nancy to live in relative comfort until her death in 1979.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley was openly homosexual after his parents' deaths, having realised his homosexuality while he was interned in Switzerland during the First World War.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley plumbed his sexuality in his writings.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He belonged to a circle of notable literary homosexuals.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] They flouted convention, specifically the homophobia that kept gay men in the closet or exposed openly gay men to legal prosecution.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] While he never found the "Ideal Friend" he wrote of so often (at least in human form), he had many long-term relationships.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley was a "twank", a term used by sailors and guardsmen to describe a man who paid for their sexual services.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He described the ritual of picking up and entertaining a young guardsman, sailor or labourer.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His memoir serves as a guide to the sexuality of a gay man of Ackerley's generation.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Auden, in his review of *My Father and Myself*, speculates that Ackerley enjoyed the "brotherly" sexual act of mutual masturbation rather than penetration.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley described himself as "quite impenetrable".
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] He encouraged Harry Daley to publish *This Small Cloud*, his account of his experiences as a gay police constable on the Bloomsbury beat (Daley was painted in his uniform by Duncan Grant).
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In October 1929, Ackerley's father, Roger Ackerley died of tertiary syphilis.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley thus discovered that his father had had a second family for more than 20 years.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Roger used to visit his daughters three or four times a year when he was supposedly travelling on business, and sometimes when out to walk his first family's dog.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] His mistress, Muriel Perry, served as a nurse during the First World War and was busy with her career; she seldom saw their three daughters: Sally and Elizabeth, twins born in 1909, and Diana, born in 1912; all were cared for by a Miss Coutts.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] The birth of the youngest was never registered but they were all given their mother's surname.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley described the lives of his half-sisters in his 1968 memoir: "They had no parental care, no family life, no friends." For years the girls thought that their father was "Uncle Bodger", who occasionally brought them gifts and money.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley looked after his father's second family without telling his mother, who died in 1946.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] For years Ackerley was obsessed with his relationship with his father, both because of the tension of his covert homosexuality and what he described as his father's domineering personality.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In his memoir, *My Father and Myself* (1969), which one reviewer termed the "mystery" of the son on the track of his father, Ackerley speculated that his father had had some homosexual experiences as a young Guardsman.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In trying to understand his father's life, he grappled with his own.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1975 Diana Perry, then Diana Petre, published a memoir, *The Secret Orchard of Roger Ackerley.* "Secret orchard" was Roger's term for his second family, used in one of his final notes to his son.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In the United States Ackerley's books have been reissued and are published solely by New York Review of Books Classics.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] In 1980 the BBC series *Omnibus* profiled Ackerley in a dramatised biography starring Benjamin Whitrow.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Entitled *We Think The World of You*, it was not an adaptation of the novel as such, although included elements of it.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Written by Tristram Powell and Paul Bailey, and directed by Powell, it won a BAFTA award in 1981.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley's sister Nancy endowed the annual J.
[src:frank-kendon/j-r-ackerley] Ackerley Prize for Autobiography, which was awarded beginning in 1982.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The **New English Bible (NEB)** is an English translation of the Bible.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The New Testament was published in 1961 and the Old Testament (with the Apocrypha) was published on 16 March 1970.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] In 1989, it was significantly revised and republished as the Revised English Bible.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Near the time when the copyright to the English Revised Version (ERV) was due to expire (1935), the Oxford University Press (OUP), and the Cambridge University Press (CUP), who were the ERV copyright holders, began investigations to determine whether a modern revision of the ERV text was necessary.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] In due time, three committees of translators and one committee of literary advisers were enlisted to produce the New English Bible.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Each of the translation committees was responsible for a different section of the Bible: the Old Testament, the Apocrypha, and the New Testament.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The work of translating was typically undertaken in this fashion: A member, or members, of one of the committees would produce a draft of a book, or books, of the Bible (typically from the section in which they were assigned) and submit the draft to the section committee.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Occasionally a scholar outside the committee would be invited to participate in this phase of the translation process and was asked to submit a draft of the book or books with which he or she had renowned experience.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] This draft was then distributed among the members of the appropriate committee.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Members of the committee would then meet and discuss the translation choices made in the draft.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The draft that resulted from this meeting of the concerned committee was then sent to the committee of literary advisers, who would revise the draft in co-operation with the translators.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] When a consensus on the draft was reached, the final draft would be sent on to the Joint Committee, which was head over the four sub-committees.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] For the Old Testament the translators primarily made use of the Masoretic Text as presented by Rudolf Kittel in his 3rd Edition of the *Biblia Hebraica* (1937).
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] In addition to the Masoretic Text, the translators also made use of the Dead Sea Scrolls, the Samaritan Pentateuch, the Greek Septuagint, the Aramaic Targums, and the Syriac *Peshitta*.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] For the Apocrypha the translators made the decision to follow *The Old Testament in Greek according to the Septuagint*, edited by Henry Barclay Swete.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] For the New Testament the New English Bible translators relied on a large body of texts including early Greek New Testament manuscripts, early translations rendered in other languages (those aside from Greek), and the quotations of early Christian writers and speakers.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The main source text of the New English Bible's New Testament can be found in *The Greek New Testament*, edited by R.V.G.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Tasker and published by the University Presses of Oxford and Cambridge (1964).
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The translators of the New English Bible chose to render their translation using a principle of translation called dynamic equivalence (also referred to as functional equivalence or thought-for-thought translation).
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] As a result, the New English Bible is necessarily more paraphrastic at times in order to render the thoughts of the original author into modern English.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Bruce declared that "To the sponsors and translators of the New English Bible the English speaking world owes an immense debt.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] They have given us a version which is contemporary in idiom, up-to-date in scholarship, attractive, and at times exciting in content".
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Eliot, however, commented that the New English Bible "astonishes in its combination of the vulgar, the trivial and the pedantic".
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Henry Gifford argued that "the new translators … kill the wonder".
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The British publisher and author Adam Nicolson, in his 2003 book on the King James Bible, criticized the newer translation for its 'anxiety not to bore or intimidate'.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The New English Bible was produced before gender-neutral language was used in translations of the Bible.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Thus, the NEB rendered pronouns (and other parts of speech) using traditional English grammatical construction, translating "he" from the original manuscripts to refer either to a male human being or to a sexually undistinguished human being.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] This traditional construction has now become controversial in some Christian circles (as in other parts of English-speaking societies), and a recent revision of the New English Bible entitled "The Revised English Bible" incorporates gender-inclusive language.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The NEB with the Apocrypha is one of the versions authorized to be used in services of the Episcopal Church.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] The Most Rev Donald Coggan, Archbishop of York (1961–1974).
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Simpson, Sir Godfrey Driver (convener), L.
[src:frank-kendon/new-english-bible] Prof Sir Roger Mynors, Prof Basil Willey, Sir Arthur Norrington, Anne Ridler, Canon Adam Fox, Dr John Carey, and the Conveners of the Translation Panels.
